< review>
UPDATE: I have now been here 4 times and still 5 stars! Tonight was my first weekend evening and wow, I had such a great experience... for the paid entertainment, unlike anywhere else where a band or DJ begin to set up while you eat and eventually play music... this is what happens... You're casually dining when a old VW bus pulls up sporting some speakers and conspicuous lighting. Guess what, its DJ Alf Alpha who ends up pulling up to the curb, parks, opens up his roof and starts spinning music with a nice sound system mounted to the vintage roof rack! There is also burning incense and a monitor showing interesting videos. This was awesome. Music is properly played starting slow and slowly evolving to hip hop and more. BRAVO
Okay onto the food. Tonight I tried the hummus again, my favorite Bianco pizza add Pepperoni, Caprese pizza add jalapeno, the Boom Boom shrimp and also the meatballs.
The meatballs are dense and have great flavor. The boom boom shrimp are coated in a Panko type of airy crispy and light breading and then smothered in a slightly spicey sticky sauce TRY THIS! The pizzas were great as usual and of course the hummus, oh the hummus. Youd typically have a hard time convincing me that a place has better hummus the most but guess what this place does. They put some sort of oil in it which adds to the flavor and the texture. I'm telling you, this place must be experienced.
Here is my original review, it's worth a read
I love this place. Really consistently good food. Nice selection of sandwiches and pizzas etc. The ingredients are all high quality and the chefs are passionate about what they do and what you're about to eat.
Hummus is really really good, served with pita that is also fresh and delicious with a tiny bit of char flavor it's so delicious.
I got one of the simple pizzas but added pepperoni which wasn't a problem and also made it an 11! Again, fresh quality ingredients over a top quality dough (slightly sweet, savory and chewy) mixed with a light but very flavorful sauce makes for one delicious pie!
This place is absolutely worth a try.
Service is A+ and food is A+</review>

< review>
Kitchen 86 is a true blessing to the desert community; food and ambiance is exceptional! Lights are dimmed enough for dates, there are enough TVs at the bar to make it a sports night, and there is also a patio section, which is perfect for casual hangouts. The closest thing to a hip, LA-Scene restaurant in the desert. The staff provides amazing customer service that should serve as an example to anyone who works in the hospitality industry. From our host Victoria, to our servers Rachel [who offered honest and informative recommendations] and Connor, I felt at home throughout the entire dinner experience. I call it an experience, because that's what you get from Kitchen 86. Amazing job. And it's also open until 2am.<//review>

(Translated by Google) It is a Vietnamese restaurant.
The menu includes various Vietnamese dishes such as pho, egg noodles, meat-based plates and fresh spring rolls.
The taste is well seasoned, and I think it tastes good with the Japanese tongue. The photo is Wonton's Pho (menu number was #31).
Most dishes are around $10, and noodles such as pho are around $8 and are reasonably priced.
*When asking for a menu, the menu number will tell you enough, so if the dish name is difficult, please try with the number.

I often use it during the daytime on weekdays, but the store is a little crowded. The parking lot is not so large, but I think it can be stopped immediately because the metabolism of cars in and out is good.

<UserId.>102665040855091385100</UserId.><Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
If you like sandwiches, you have to at least try Jersey Mikes. The sandwiches are freshly made, including the bread. The food is very filling and the price is good. My favorite menu item is the number 7, Mike's way. If you have kids, I recommend that you purchase the mini size for them. The only down side is that the parking is limited, but they are on the delivery apps.<//Text>

<Review>Love the Subs at Jersey Mikes. Recently had a problem with some confusion as either JM or Postmates charged me an extra $5.22 even though I checked "order pickup" and drove there to get my food. Jersey Mikes made good on it, gave me a gift card for a free sub and an apology email for another free sub. Postmates was absolutly NO HELP AT ALL when I contacted them. <user>106189643616986771222</user><name>Nick Patterson</name><Date>1534465918176< /Date><rating>5</rating>< review>
The service here is excellent. From time to time I walk here from work, about 8 minutes each way. Food shows up very quickly and beer right away so if I stick to my hour lunch and don't go over I'm always on time.

It's priced well and the burritos can be eaten in halves if so inclined. They're large.

I prefer to sit out on the patio which is a wonderful space with full shade and a good draft to stay cool. If no one is out there (or at least im up wind and sitting at the other end) I'll smoke while sipping said beer and have never been asked not to. Another huge plus for me.

Finally, if you're a sports person, there are TVs tuned to 6-8 different channels depending on if there are local games to watch or not.

I highly recommend this as either lunch or dinner. Great date spot too.</review>

<Rating>1<//Rating>< Review>
6:00 on a Thursday. Sat at the bar directly in front where the bartender makes drinks.  The place was only 20% occupied.  Took her 10 minutes to ask me what I wanted to drink.  Ordered the drink and asked for a menu because I wanted to eat.  Got the drink, utensils and a napkin ...No menu.  Had to walk around to find one.  Sat there for 15 more minutes being ignored listening to them talk to each other about their lives.  TWO bartenders could not find the time in their busy night, there are only 5 people sitting at the bar, to ask me for my food order.  Left 5 bucks on the bar and walked out.  Typical service at Taco Loco.  It can be fun to meet new friends but don't expect to get any service.

Drove to Casa Ramo and was ate there.  I had my food within 10 minutes of entering Casa Ramos.<//Review>

<UserId.>114516130128373934017< /UserId.><name>April Preisler<//name><date>1610840995309</date><Rate>2<//Rate>< Review>
I recently moved to Auburn and finally made it over to Ikeda's after all of the rave reviews. I have to say that I was less than impressed with the food and it is extremely overpriced. My burger was mediocre and my husband ordered a specialty burger that was so messy that he had to take off half of the toppings just to get through it. The onion rings didn't taste fresh, but like frozen onion rings. The fries were somewhat soggy. Paying $35 for lunch for 2 seemed like a huge waste. I won't be returning.

The store itself is cute and packs a lot of fun snacks, pies, cheese and meats. May stop here for that, but not the food.</Review>

101633823983630250882< /user_id>
<user_name>Jason Nash< /user_name>< Date>
1562573341386<//Date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
<Review>"Nice picture, Jason.  A demolished piece of pie?  Really?"

Yeah.  Meant to take more and better photos, but after a fun day swimming at the North Fork of the American River, we were hungry, and I was only reminded to take pictures at this point.

In a way this is very representative of Ikeda's.  The food is so good, it will be gone before you know it.

Pictured is a slice (mostly) of Triple Berry Pie.  Almost as excellent as either of their Razzleberry options (cobbler or pie, both magnificent).

You have to try the Marionberry shake.  And then everyone you know must try it.

Other musts:

*Truffle Parmesan Fries.  Holy heck.

*Ikeda's Gourmet Wagyu Burger.  Be hungry

*the Patty Melt.  No, really, the Patty Melt.

*Finally, the Teriyaki burger has no pineapple, but uses caramelized onions instead.  It's so sweet and tasty that I probably had it three times before I realized it.

This is one of my must-stops returning to Reno from any California trip.

Did I mention the farm fresh produce and collection of homemade sauces?

There are so many reasons to love Ikeda's.

< review>
This place is one of my favorite on earth! I don't get much occasion to stop any more but was in the area helping take care of my mom recently and when I realized we were close to Ikeda's, I knew I would be stopping for a pie (at least). Fantastic selection of fresh produce, pies, wine, dried fruit, jams, candy... and they have a burger stand type restaurant at one end, as well. I feel like I must be their "target market / customer" because everything works for me here!<//review>

< review>
Fun little market.  Definitely a go to if you're in the area.  I would suggest between 11 and. 1130 for lunch.  By noon it was packed,  no parking and a never ending line for food and checkout at the store. I would suggest sharing a double patty burger because they were thin patties with big buns, better meat to bread ratio.  The apple pie was good, but a little sugar and cinnamon on the crust would've made it delicious.  I wasn't sure about going with all the reviews,  but overall a great experience.  The knocked out the orders really fast and everyone had a great attitude.</review>

< user>
115008902337261967313<//user>
<name>Scott Smith</name><date>1594269090678< /date><rating>2< /rating>< text>
I'm a big fan of family owned shops, but not when they aren't taking care of their own store or investing any money into it.  I have seen the Ikeda market for decades growing up in the area but had never stopped in, so I decided to finally see for myself today.  The restaurant side of the building was old and filthy, there was food in the blinds, flies all around, and worn out tables and chairs that looked 30 years old.  The food was decent, but overpriced ($15 for a burger and fries).  Walked through the market section afterwards, it was nicer and gave off a farmers market vibe, but still pricey.  You can tell the fruits and veggies come from outside suppliers and the "specialty" jams, jellies, and other items are mass produced.  This place has been open long enough and has enough traffic that the Ikeda family should really have invested more money in fixing up their place or pricing goods for better value.  Overall it was a disappointment to me.</text>

<user_id>115008902337261967313</user_id>< name>
Scott Smith<//name>
<Date>1594269090678</Date><Rating>2</Rating><review>I'm a big fan of family owned shops, but not when they aren't taking care of their own store or investing any money into it.  I have seen the Ikeda market for decades growing up in the area but had never stopped in, so I decided to finally see for myself today.  The restaurant side of the building was old and filthy, there was food in the blinds, flies all around, and worn out tables and chairs that looked 30 years old.  The food was decent, but overpriced ($15 for a burger and fries).  Walked through the market section afterwards, it was nicer and gave off a farmers market vibe, but still pricey.  You can tell the fruits and veggies come from outside suppliers and the "specialty" jams, jellies, and other items are mass produced.  This place has been open long enough and has enough traffic that the Ikeda family should really have invested more money in fixing up their place or pricing goods for better value.  Overall it was a disappointment to me.<//review><Pics>None< /Pics><resp>None</resp><GmapID>0x809b056a04c55c77:0xb242bebb67a4ca5b< /GmapID></record>

< Text>
Stopped by Ikeda's after a round of golf in Auburn.  What a great decision.  It was very busy and parking was a challenge, but I think this is related to everyone returning from Tahoe on a Sunday.  We stopped by for lunch as well as to pick up some fruit and pies.

Lunch rating: 4/5
Fruit ratings: 5/5
Pie Rating: 5+/5 ... probably the best apple pie I've had in the Sac area (far better than apple hill).

The teriyaki burger was good, the fries were good, but I couldn't get over how many flies there were (probably unavoidable as a fruit stand), but I didn't know what to expect.  I wouldn't classify the place as dirty though.  It was clean.  The staff was friendly and the owner said Hi.  The peaches I bought were amazing, and again the apple pie was simply the best.  Glad to have found Ikeda's.<//Text>

We stop at Ikedas every time we head to Lake Tahoe every August. The annual pie is something to look forward to sharing as a family. This year was a huge disappointment! We purchased a $20 peach cobbler and it was like a pie crust filled with gelatin. It tasted bland, there may have been two peaches in the entire pie. It was like a peach jello with no flavor. <date>1527027630183< /date><rate>5</rate>< Review>
Of all the places you could stop on your way back West from Tahoe, this is one of the best. The burgers and pot pie are so good ‚Äì not health for you, but tasty. Usually great food I've recommended this to multiple people and brought many people here. I discovered it because my resident with ms had me call and pick up food for him all the time. < Review>
Someone told me they had the best burgers in town here so I decided to try it out. Then I remembered seeing Ikeda's on TV and decided I wanted to try it. I have mixed feelings about it.
I tried the Gourmet Wagyu Burger since it came with grass fed beef. It was a truly wonderful burger. Not sure what I was tasting that was so good, maybe the hint of truffle or maybe the cheese. I would have preferred they keep that mountain of fries and trim $2 off the hefty price tag, and 2 pounds of fat.
Wash your hands before you get there. You will lose your appetite when you walk past all the rotting food on the way back to the restrooms. Totally unacceptable. Many of the items in the store are not priced. I could not find anyone to ask, and I wasn't about to wait in line to get a surprise at the checkstand.<//Review>

<review>I was taken to this restaurant by a friend of mine!  This friend of mine was excited to eat here as we were passing though town!  We arrived at dinner time and proceeded to order our food!  The menu is easy to understand and order from (being from cowboy country in Nevada i was not in anyway interested in the hipster/vegan options but what can you expect in California?)! I ordered the double buger with cheese,  regular fries,  drink,  and a slice of apple pie!!  My complete order came to about $21 (((((whoah))))) maybe it will be worth it once i taste it!! I had ticket number 98 and they were serving people with ticket number of 70-75, so i would be in for a long wait, but its ok,  i will just get some Dr Pepper  and chill. The Dr Pepper ended up being mostly soda water and pretty nasty, just enough to not feel like complaining but gross enough to not enjoy it!  Ended up not chilling though,  the air conditioning was obviously not working,  it was hotter inside then outside!!  Miserable!!!!!  However the grocery store section was perfectly fine and cold!! Finally after 30-40 mins my order was ready! First thing, the fries were just at that point where they were warm enough to be edible but a minute later they were cold soggy fries, only edible dipped in ketchup (if your fries cant be eaten by themselves with no seasoning or sauses,  are they really that good?)!  They were at least home made looking?!  Now the burger?  The patties were miniscule at best and dry to the squeeze,  no juices flowing from them!  They were super thin and cooked pass well done!  The cheese and condiments were good, but the meat is what makes a good burger,  i remember back in my childhood my dad cooking burgers as thick as chicken breast!!! So unless the meat is cooked to satisfaction, what is the point of eating it? The dutch apple pie had tons of flavor and seemed like it was made with tasty apples!  I am not sure about "Dutch Apple Pie", but i am pretty sure that the bottom crust should be cooked solid and be flacky not just raw dough!!

So once again I think I have found one of those restaurants that is cool and hip to go to, (like IN n Out)  so thats the only reason they are open,  not because they serve us great food all the time!  Hopefully this was just a bad day for them?  I will give any restaurant a second chance, and i will do the same here!!

Happy Eating!!!!</review><pics>None< /pics>< resp>

I was taken to this restaurant by a friend of mine!  This friend of mine was excited to eat here as we were passing though town!  We arrived at dinner time and proceeded to order our food!  The menu is easy to understand and order from (being from cowboy country in Nevada i was not in anyway interested in the hipster/vegan options but what can you expect in California?)! I ordered the double buger with cheese,  regular fries,  drink,  and a slice of apple pie!!  My complete order came to about $21 (((((whoah))))) maybe it will be worth it once i taste it!! I had ticket number 98 and they were serving people with ticket number of 70-75, so i would be in for a long wait, but its ok,  i will just get some Dr Pepper  and chill. The Dr Pepper ended up being mostly soda water and pretty nasty, just enough to not feel like complaining but gross enough to not enjoy it!  Ended up not chilling though,  the air conditioning was obviously not working,  it was hotter inside then outside!!  Miserable!!!!!  However the grocery store section was perfectly fine and cold!! Finally after 30-40 mins my order was ready! First thing, the fries were just at that point where they were warm enough to be edible but a minute later they were cold soggy fries, only edible dipped in ketchup (if your fries cant be eaten by themselves with no seasoning or sauses,  are they really that good?)!  They were at least home made looking?!  Now the burger?  The patties were miniscule at best and dry to the squeeze,  no juices flowing from them!  They were super thin and cooked pass well done!  The cheese and condiments were good, but the meat is what makes a good burger,  i remember back in my childhood my dad cooking burgers as thick as chicken breast!!! So unless the meat is cooked to satisfaction, what is the point of eating it? The dutch apple pie had tons of flavor and seemed like it was made with tasty apples!  I am not sure about "Dutch Apple Pie", but i am pretty sure that the bottom crust should be cooked solid and be flacky not just raw dough!!

So once again I think I have found one of those restaurants that is cool and hip to go to, (like IN n Out)  so thats the only reason they are open,  not because they serve us great food all the time!  Hopefully this was just a bad day for them?  I will give any restaurant a second chance, and i will do the same here!!

Happy Eating!!!!</Text>

<UserId.>108833816486311466401</UserId.><user_name>autumnpumpkin T.< /user_name><Date>1503086795783<//Date>< Rate>
3</Rate>
< Review>
Great place to stop by! Friendly staff and great customer service! The pies are a little expensive, but good. Some are extremely sweet since either used with canned or real fruit or half. Sometimes the pies have seeds or stem in them-depending on if they were used with real or canned fruit. Good pie choices! Recommend the Peach "Cobbler" though its technically not a Cobbler but a pie. Variety of Fries-would not recommend the small/thin fries since they are overcooked. The freezes inside can be refreshing on a hot day. Yet they are very icy and I mostly get balls of ice in the cups-but once in a while its nice.
The food varies on preparation time. 5-15min. The Salmon sandwich is good-would recommend it, however they did down size the amount of salmon on it by shredding it into small pieces to make it appear as a lot. Also reduced the veggies on it-I had a sliver of pepper and wasn't really happy with that-and a little too oily-even though the sub tasted pretty good. The ranch has added water to it so they can give out more.

There is an outdoor seating area as well as inside. I do love sitting outside!
Would recommend that they have a sign regarding have your dog on a leash, so people can be conscientious of others and for their own  dog's safety of running in the street.<//Review>

<UserId.>108519650391730490345</UserId.><Name>Rick Irvin< /Name><time>1563648048925< /time>< Rating>
1<//Rating>
< review>
There was a significant number if flies inside the burger shack. I get that people come in and out of the door and flies will inevitably get in. However, they have blowers which could help mitigate this and would recommend investing in these.

Personally, the flies were disgusting. After seeing flies crawling on the tip of the mayonnaise dispenser (on the actual business end of the dispenser where the Mayo comes out), I skipped the Mayo. I grabbed a little ketchup and as I was spreading the kethup on my bun, one of the flies landed on my burger. At this point I said f#$& it and threw my burger out and left. Flies crawl around on all sorts of disgusting stuff. If I can see them crawling around on patrons food, I can only imagine what a horror show it is in the kitchen<//review>

113221843215824901865</userid>
<username>Karen Lawson</username>< date>
1506577522495<//date>
< Rating>
4< /Rating>
< text>
Ikeda's is a traditional stop for those traveling East or West between Reno and Sacramento. It offers  a cafe and grocery featuring produce  grown by local farmers. It's also famous for baked goods including freshly baked fruit pies and cobblers. Ikeda's produces condiments and dressings including its family recipe teriyaki sauce. The selection is great, but beware: The prices are not for the faint of heart or a thin wallet. Pies cost nearly 20 bucks. Not bad for an annual stop, but be ready for sticker shock.</text>

< review>
Overall, I would not eat her again for a couple of reasons. We ordered a bacon cheese burger with fries and a shake but ended up getting a veggie burger instead. This was not a problem as they quickly fix the issue and prepared us a burger however the burger tasted really weird like it had some sort of cinnamon Spice in it. There was also what I consider to be somewhat of a health problem, I asked if they had ranch when the girl was ringing this up and she pointed to some ranch on the counter. There were several little plastic tubs of ranch inside of a big plastic Square tub that weren't refrigerated. Of course I was sketchy on this because it was Dairy but I did go over and pick one of them up to at least see if it was cold, it was not. I would not want to risk eating a hamburger or anything else that is being prepared by people that do not understand the basics of chilling food such as dairy. It is also very pricey, it was $15 for a shake fries and a burger, thank God we split it especially since I didn't eat my half and left it on the table.< /review>

<Review>I went there earlier today on my way home back to NV.  I had their garden burger, which the base consisted of rice, and it was delicious.  It was very tasty, and being vegetarian, I absolutely love that they have alternatives, including tofu burger.  The fries are delicious and most definitely fresh, rather than frozen fake-fries, as my ex would say.  Upon checking out their menu, I saw that they have several different flavors of milkshakes, all of which contain real fruit.  I opted to try the banana milkshake, and it was the most delicious milkshake I've ever tasted.  Next time, I plan on trying their marionberry milkshake, as that sounds delicious.  They are always crowded, and it's for a good reason.  Ikeda's truly is amazing.<//Review>< Pics>

< Review>
Their tri-tip was a roast beef sandwich au juice.   Don't get me wrong, but it wasn't the typical BBQ tri-tip sandwich.   It even came with au juice.  The toast beef looked just like cheesesteak thin beef, they actually have a cheesesteak sandwich on the menu.  It also came with thinly sliced onions, just like a cheesesteak sandwich.  The roll was also very cheesesteak-eaque.   With an au juice dip on the side.
But it was good.
The regular fries were hot and delicious.</Review>
